# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: abraham-kuyper
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:abraham-kuyper/1894-dutch-general-election] General elections were held in the Netherlands on 10 April 1894, with a second round in 27 constituencies on 24 April.
[src:abraham-kuyper/1894-dutch-general-election] The Liberal Union and the dissident Free Liberals remained the largest group, winning 60 of the 100 seats in the House of Representatives.
[src:abraham-kuyper/1894-dutch-general-election] Of the 100 seats in the House of Representatives, 79 were elected in single-member constituencies using the two-round system.
[src:abraham-kuyper/1894-dutch-general-election] The other 21 were elected using two-round plurality block voting in 5 constituencies from 2 to 9 seats.
[src:abraham-kuyper/1894-dutch-general-election] To be elected in the first round, a candidate had to reach an electoral threshold of 50% of the number of valid votes cast, divided by the number of seats up for election in the district.
[src:abraham-kuyper/1894-dutch-general-election] Several candidates ran in multiple districts.
[src:abraham-kuyper/1894-dutch-general-election] When they won in more than one seat they picked which seat to take.
[src:abraham-kuyper/1894-dutch-general-election] As a result, several by-elections took place shortly after the general election, leading to the Liberal Union having 32 seats in total, the Free Liberals 25, the ARP 7 seats and the Free Anti-Revolutionaries 8.
[src:abraham-kuyper/1897-dutch-general-election] General elections were held in the Netherlands on 15 June 1897, with a second round in 50 constituencies on 25 June.
[src:abraham-kuyper/1897-dutch-general-election] The Liberal Union remained the largest party, winning 38 of the 100 seats in the House of Representatives.
[src:abraham-kuyper/1897-dutch-general-election] The 100 seats in the House of Representatives were elected in single-member constituencies using the two-round system.
[src:abraham-kuyper/1901-dutch-general-election] General elections were held in the Netherlands on 14 June 1901, with a second round in some constituencies on 27 June.
[src:abraham-kuyper/1901-dutch-general-election] The Catholic group became the largest in the House of Representatives, winning 25 of the 100 seats.
[src:abraham-kuyper/1901-dutch-general-election] As a result, several by-elections took place shortly after the general election.
[src:abraham-kuyper/1905-dutch-general-election] General elections were held in the Netherlands on 16 June 1905, with a second round in some constituencies on 28 June.
[src:abraham-kuyper/1905-dutch-general-election] The General League of Roman Catholic Electoral Associations and the Liberal Union emerged as the largest party, winning each 25 of the 100 seats in the House of Representatives.
[src:abraham-kuyper/1909-dutch-general-election] General elections were held in the Netherlands on 11 June 1909, with a second round in some constituencies on 23 June.
[src:abraham-kuyper/1909-dutch-general-election] The General League of Roman Catholic Electoral Associations emerged as the largest party, winning 25 of the 100 seats in the House of Representatives.
[src:abraham-kuyper/abraham-kuyper] In addition, he founded the Vrije Universiteit Amsterdam, the Anti-Revolutionary Party, and a newspaper.
[src:abraham-kuyper/abraham-kuyper] He vigorously denounced modernism in theology as a fad that would die out.
[src:abraham-kuyper/abraham-kuyper] In politics, he dominated the Anti-Revolutionary Party (ARP) from its founding in 1879 to his death in 1920.
[src:abraham-kuyper/abraham-kuyper] He promoted pillarisation, the social expression of the anti-thesis in public life, whereby Protestant, Catholic and secular elements each had their own independent schools, universities and social organisations.
[src:abraham-kuyper/abraham-kuyper] Abraham Kuyper was born on 29 October 1837 in Maassluis, Netherlands.
[src:abraham-kuyper/abraham-kuyper] His father Jan Frederik Kuyper served as a minister for the Dutch Reformed Church in Hoogmade, Maassluis, Middelburg and Leiden.
[src:abraham-kuyper/abraham-kuyper] The boy received no formal primary education, but received secondary education at the Gymnasium of Leiden.
[src:abraham-kuyper/abraham-kuyper] In 1855, he graduated from the Gymnasium and began to study literature, philosophy and theology at Leiden University.
[src:abraham-kuyper/abraham-kuyper] He received his propaedeuse in literature in 1857, and summa cum laude in philosophy in 1858.
[src:abraham-kuyper/abraham-kuyper] He also took classes in Arabic, Armenian and physics.
[src:abraham-kuyper/abraham-kuyper] In comparing the views of John Calvin and Jan Łaski, Kuyper showed a clear sympathy for the more liberal Łaski.
[src:abraham-kuyper/abraham-kuyper] During his studies, Kuyper was a member of the modern tendency within the Dutch Reformed Church.
[src:abraham-kuyper/abraham-kuyper] In May 1862, he was declared eligible for the ministry, and in 1863, he accepted a call to become minister for the Dutch Reformed Church for the town of Beesd.
[src:abraham-kuyper/abraham-kuyper] In the same year he married Johanna Hendrika Schaay (1842–1899).
[src:abraham-kuyper/abraham-kuyper] In 1864 he began corresponding with the anti-revolutionary MP Guillaume Groen van Prinsterer, who heavily influenced his political and theological views (see below).
[src:abraham-kuyper/abraham-kuyper] Around 1866, he began to sympathise with the orthodox tendency within the Dutch Reformed Church.
[src:abraham-kuyper/abraham-kuyper] He was inspired by the robust reformed faith of Pietje Baltus, a single woman in her early 30s, the daughter of a miller.
[src:abraham-kuyper/abraham-kuyper] He began to oppose the centralization in the church, the role of the King and began to plead for the separation of church and state.
[src:abraham-kuyper/abraham-kuyper] In 1867, Kuyper was asked to become minister for the parish in Utrecht and he left Beesd.
[src:abraham-kuyper/abraham-kuyper] In 1870 he was asked to come to Amsterdam.
[src:abraham-kuyper/abraham-kuyper] In 1871 he began to write for the *De Heraut* (*The Herald*).
[src:abraham-kuyper/abraham-kuyper] In 1872, he founded his own paper, *De Standaard* (*The Standard*).
[src:abraham-kuyper/abraham-kuyper] This paper laid the foundation for the network of Reformed organisation (the Reformed pillar), which Kuyper founded.
[src:abraham-kuyper/abraham-kuyper] In 1886, Kuyper led an exodus from the Dutch Reformed Church.
[src:abraham-kuyper/abraham-kuyper] He grieved the loss of Reformed distinctives within the State Church, which no longer required office bearers to agree to the Reformed standards which had once been foundational.
[src:abraham-kuyper/abraham-kuyper] Kuyper and the consistory of Amsterdam insisted that both ministers and church members subscribe to the Reformed confessions.
[src:abraham-kuyper/abraham-kuyper] This was appealed to the classis, and Kuyper, along with about eighty members of the Amsterdam consistory, were suspended in December 1885.
[src:abraham-kuyper/abraham-kuyper] This was appealed to the provincial synod, which upheld the ruling in a 1 July 1886 ruling.
[src:abraham-kuyper/abraham-kuyper] Refusing to accept his suspension, Kuyper preached to his followers in an auditorium on Sunday, 11 July 1886.
[src:abraham-kuyper/abraham-kuyper] Because of their deep sorrow at the state of the Dutch Reformed Church, the group called itself the *Doleantie* (grieving ones).
[src:abraham-kuyper/abraham-kuyper] By 1889, the *Doleantie* churches had over 200 congregations, 180,000 members, and about 80 ministers.
[src:abraham-kuyper/abraham-kuyper] Kuyper, although at first antagonistic towards them, soon began to seek union with the churches of the Secession of 1834, the *Christelijke Gereformeerde Kerken* (Christian Reformed Church).
[src:abraham-kuyper/abraham-kuyper] These churches had earlier broken off from the Dutch Reformed Church.
[src:abraham-kuyper/abraham-kuyper] This union was effected in 1892, and the *Gereformeerde Kerken in Nederland* (Reformed Churches in the Netherlands) was formed.
[src:abraham-kuyper/abraham-kuyper] This denomination has its counterpart in the Christian Reformed Church in North America.
[src:abraham-kuyper/abraham-kuyper] He strongly opposed modernism in theology, viewing it as a new-fangled fad based on a superficial view of reality.
[src:abraham-kuyper/abraham-kuyper] He argued that modernism missed the reality of God, of prayer, of sin, and of the church.
[src:abraham-kuyper/abraham-kuyper] He said modernism would eventually prove as useless as 'A Squeezed Out Lemon Peel,' while traditional religious truths would survive.
[src:abraham-kuyper/abraham-kuyper] In his lectures at Princeton in 1898, he argued that Calvinism was more than theology—it provided a comprehensive worldview and indeed had already proven to be a major positive factor in the development of the institutions and values of modern society.
[src:abraham-kuyper/abraham-kuyper] In 1873, Kuyper stood as candidate in the general election for parliament for the constituency of Gouda, but he was defeated by the incumbent member of parliament, the conservative Jonkheer Willem Maurits de Brauw (1810–1874).
[src:abraham-kuyper/abraham-kuyper] When De Brauw died the next year, Kuyper stood again in the by-election for the same district.
[src:abraham-kuyper/abraham-kuyper] This time he was elected to parliament, defeating the liberal candidate Herman Verners van der Loeff.
[src:abraham-kuyper/abraham-kuyper] Kuyper subsequently moved to The Hague, without telling his friends in Amsterdam.
[src:abraham-kuyper/abraham-kuyper] In parliament he showed a particular interest in education, especially the equal financing of public and religious schools.
[src:abraham-kuyper/abraham-kuyper] In 1876, he wrote "Our Program" which laid the foundation for the Anti-Revolutionary Party.
[src:abraham-kuyper/abraham-kuyper] In this programme he formulated the principle of antithesis, the conflict between the religious (Reformed and Catholics) and non-religious.
[src:abraham-kuyper/abraham-kuyper] More broadly, this programme articulated his broader political philosophy, emphasizing the proper role of government among the other spheres of life, including the family and the church.
[src:abraham-kuyper/abraham-kuyper] Kuyper argued that government's authority, like all human authority, derived from God's authority.
[src:abraham-kuyper/abraham-kuyper] In 1877, he left parliament because of problems with his health, suffering from overexertion.
[src:abraham-kuyper/abraham-kuyper] In 1878, Kuyper returned to politics, he led the petition against a new law on education, which would further disadvantage religious schools.
[src:abraham-kuyper/abraham-kuyper] This was an important impetus for the foundation of the Anti-Revolutionary Party (ARP) in 1879, of which Kuyper was chairman between 1879 and 1905.
[src:abraham-kuyper/abraham-kuyper] He was the undisputed leader of the party between 1879 and 1920.
[src:abraham-kuyper/abraham-kuyper] His followers gave him the nickname "Abraham de Geweldenaar" (Abraham the Masterful).
[src:abraham-kuyper/abraham-kuyper] In 1880, he founded the Free University in Amsterdam and he was made professor of Theology there.
[src:abraham-kuyper/abraham-kuyper] He also served as its first rector magnificus.
[src:abraham-kuyper/abraham-kuyper] In 1881, he also became professor of literature.
[src:abraham-kuyper/abraham-kuyper] In 1886, he left the Dutch Reformed Church, with a large group of followers.
[src:abraham-kuyper/abraham-kuyper] The parish in Amsterdam was made independent of the church, and kept their own building.
[src:abraham-kuyper/abraham-kuyper] Between 1886 and 1892, they were called the *Dolerenden* (those with grievances).
[src:abraham-kuyper/abraham-kuyper] In 1892, those Dolerenden founded a new denomination called The Reformed Churches in the Netherlands after merging with other orthodox Reformed people who had seceded from the Dutch Reformed Church in 1834.
[src:abraham-kuyper/abraham-kuyper] In the general election of 1894, Kuyper was re-elected to the House of Representatives for the district of Sliedrecht.
[src:abraham-kuyper/abraham-kuyper] He defeated the liberal Van Haaften and the anti-takkian anti-revolutionary Beelaerts van Blokland.
[src:abraham-kuyper/abraham-kuyper] He also ran as a candidate in Dordrecht and Amsterdam, but was defeated there.
[src:abraham-kuyper/abraham-kuyper] In the election he joined the so-called Takkians, in a conflict between the liberal minister Tak, and a majority House of Representatives.
[src:abraham-kuyper/abraham-kuyper] Tak wanted to reform the census-suffrage, but a majority in parliament rejected his proposal.
[src:abraham-kuyper/abraham-kuyper] Kuyper favoured the legislation because he expected the enfranchised lower class voters would favour his party.
[src:abraham-kuyper/abraham-kuyper] This orientation towards the lower classes gave him the nickname "The bellringer of the common people" (*klokkenist van de kleine luyden*).
[src:abraham-kuyper/abraham-kuyper] His position on suffrage also led to a conflict within the ARP: a group around Alexander de Savornin Lohman was opposed on principle to universal suffrage because they rejected popular sovereignty; they left the ARP to found the CHU in 1901.
[src:abraham-kuyper/abraham-kuyper] The authoritarian leadership of Kuyper also played an important role in this conflict.
[src:abraham-kuyper/abraham-kuyper] Lohman opposed party discipline and wanted MPs to make up their own mind, while Kuyper favoured strong leadership.
[src:abraham-kuyper/abraham-kuyper] After the elections Kuyper became chair of the parliamentary caucus of the ARP.
[src:abraham-kuyper/abraham-kuyper] In his second term as MP he concentrated on more issues than education, like suffrage, labour, and foreign policy.
[src:abraham-kuyper/abraham-kuyper] In foreign affairs especially the Second Boer War was of particular interest to him, in the conflict between the Dutch-speaking reformed farmers and the English-speaking Anglicans he sided with the Boers, and heavily opposed the English.
[src:abraham-kuyper/abraham-kuyper] In 1896, Kuyper voted against the new suffrage law of Van Houten, because according to Kuyper the reforms did not go far enough.
[src:abraham-kuyper/abraham-kuyper] In the 1897 elections, Kuyper competed in Zuidhorn, Sliedrecht and Amsterdam.
[src:abraham-kuyper/abraham-kuyper] He was defeated by liberals in Zuidhorn and Amsterdam, but he defeated the liberal Wisboom in Sliedrecht.
[src:abraham-kuyper/abraham-kuyper] In Amsterdam he was defeated by Johannes Tak van Poortvliet.
[src:abraham-kuyper/abraham-kuyper] As an MP, Kuyper kept his job as journalist, and he even became chair of the Dutch Circle of Journalists in 1898; when he left in 1901 he was made honorary president.
[src:abraham-kuyper/abraham-kuyper] In the same year, at the invitation of B.B.
[src:abraham-kuyper/abraham-kuyper] Warfield, Kuyper delivered the "Stone Lectures" at Princeton Seminary, which was his first widespread exposure to a North American audience.
[src:abraham-kuyper/abraham-kuyper] These lectures were given 10–11 October 14 and 19–21 in 1898.
[src:abraham-kuyper/abraham-kuyper] He discusses the relationship of Calvinism with philosophy, religion, politics, science, art and the future.
[src:abraham-kuyper/abraham-kuyper] He also received an honorary doctorate in law there.
[src:abraham-kuyper/abraham-kuyper] During his time in the United States, he also traveled to address several Dutch Reformed congregations in Michigan and Iowa and Presbyterian gatherings in Ohio and New Jersey.
[src:abraham-kuyper/abraham-kuyper] In the 1901 elections, Kuyper was re-elected in Sliedrecht, defeating the liberal De Klerk.
[src:abraham-kuyper/abraham-kuyper] In Amsterdam he was defeated again, now by the freethinking liberal Nolting.
[src:abraham-kuyper/abraham-kuyper] He did not take his seat in parliament however but was instead appointed formateur and later prime minister of the Dutch cabinet.
[src:abraham-kuyper/abraham-kuyper] He also served as minister of Home Affairs.
[src:abraham-kuyper/abraham-kuyper] He originally wanted to become minister of labour and enterprise, but neither Mackay or Heemskerk, prominent anti-revolutionaries, wanted to become minister of Home Affairs, forcing him to take the portfolio.
[src:abraham-kuyper/abraham-kuyper] During his time as prime minister he showed a strong leadership style: he changed the rules of procedure of cabinet in order to become chair of cabinet for four years (before him, the chairmanship of the cabinet had rotated among its members).
[src:abraham-kuyper/abraham-kuyper] The portfolio of home affairs at the time was very broad: it involved local government, industrial relations, education and public morality.
[src:abraham-kuyper/abraham-kuyper] The 1903 railway strike was one of the decisive issues for his cabinet.
[src:abraham-kuyper/abraham-kuyper] Kuyper produced several particularly harsh laws to end the strikes (the so-called "worgwetten", strangling laws), and pushed them through parliament.
[src:abraham-kuyper/abraham-kuyper] He also proposed legislation to improve working conditions; however only those on fishing and harbour construction passed through parliament.
[src:abraham-kuyper/abraham-kuyper] In education Kuyper changed several education laws to improve the financial situation of religious schools.
[src:abraham-kuyper/abraham-kuyper] His law on higher education, which would make the diplomas of faith-based universities equal to that of the public universities, was defeated in the Senate.
[src:abraham-kuyper/abraham-kuyper] Consequently, Kuyper dissolved the Senate and, after a new one was elected, the legislation was accepted.
[src:abraham-kuyper/abraham-kuyper] He was also heavily involved in foreign policy, giving him the nickname "Minister of Foreign Travels".
[src:abraham-kuyper/abraham-kuyper] In 1905, his ARP lost the elections and was confined to opposition, a defeat Kuyper later blamed on the ‘disloyalty and apostasy’ of Andries Staalman, who had broken away to form the Christian Democratic Party.
[src:abraham-kuyper/abraham-kuyper] Between 1905 and 1907, Kuyper made a grand tour around the Mediterranean.
[src:abraham-kuyper/abraham-kuyper] In 1907, Kuyper became honorary doctor at the Delft University of Technology.
[src:abraham-kuyper/abraham-kuyper] In 1907, he was re-elected chair of the ARP, a post which he held until his death in 1920.
[src:abraham-kuyper/abraham-kuyper] In 1907, Kuyper wanted to return to parliament.
[src:abraham-kuyper/abraham-kuyper] In a by-election in Sneek he needed the support of the local CHU.
[src:abraham-kuyper/abraham-kuyper] This led to a personal conflict between Kuyper and De Savorin Lohman.
[src:abraham-kuyper/abraham-kuyper] In 1908, he came into conflict with Heemskerk, who had not involved him in the formation of the CHU/ARP/Catholic General League cabinet, thereby denying him the chance to return as minister.
[src:abraham-kuyper/abraham-kuyper] In 1908, Kuyper received the honorary title of minister of state.
[src:abraham-kuyper/abraham-kuyper] He was elected to the House of Representatives for the district of Ommen in the by-elections in the same year, defeating the liberal De Meester.
[src:abraham-kuyper/abraham-kuyper] He also ran in Sneek where he was elected as sole candidate.
[src:abraham-kuyper/abraham-kuyper] In 1909, he was made chair of the committee that prepared the new orthography of the Dutch language.
[src:abraham-kuyper/abraham-kuyper] In the same year he also received an honorary doctorate at the Catholic University of Leuven.
[src:abraham-kuyper/abraham-kuyper] In the 1909 elections he was re-elected in Ommen, defeating the liberal Teesselink, but he was defeated in Dordrecht by the liberal De Kanter.
[src:abraham-kuyper/abraham-kuyper] In 1909, he came under heavy criticism in the so-called decorations affairs (*lintjeszaak*).
[src:abraham-kuyper/abraham-kuyper] While minister of home affairs, Kuyper allegedly received money from one Rudolf Lehman, to make him Officer in the Order of Orange-Nassau.
[src:abraham-kuyper/abraham-kuyper] A parliamentary debate was held on the subject and a committee was instituted to research the claim.
[src:abraham-kuyper/abraham-kuyper] In 1910, the committee reported that Kuyper was innocent.
[src:abraham-kuyper/abraham-kuyper] Between 1910 and 1912, he was member of the committee headed by Heemskerk, which prepared a revision of the constitution.
[src:abraham-kuyper/abraham-kuyper] In 1912, he resigned his seat in parliament for health reasons, but he returned to politics in the following year, this time as a member of the Senate for the province of South Holland.
[src:abraham-kuyper/abraham-kuyper] In 1913, he was made commander in the Order of the Netherlands Lion.
[src:abraham-kuyper/abraham-kuyper] During the First World War Kuyper sided with the Germans, because he had opposed the English since the Boer wars.
[src:abraham-kuyper/abraham-kuyper] In 1918, Kuyper played an important role in the formation of the first cabinet led by Charles Ruijs de Beerenbrouck.
[src:abraham-kuyper/abraham-kuyper] In 1920, at the age of 83 Kuyper died in The Hague and was buried amid great public attention.
[src:abraham-kuyper/abraham-kuyper] Kuyper's theological and political views are linked.
[src:abraham-kuyper/abraham-kuyper] His orthodox Protestant beliefs heavily influenced his anti-revolutionary politics.
[src:abraham-kuyper/abraham-kuyper] In 1905 there was a higher education law enacted, but Kuyper was against this and became part of the opposition.
[src:abraham-kuyper/abraham-kuyper] Theologically Kuyper has also been very influential.
[src:abraham-kuyper/abraham-kuyper] He opposed the liberal tendencies within the Dutch Reformed Church.
[src:abraham-kuyper/abraham-kuyper] This eventually led to secession and the foundation of Reformed Churches in the Netherlands.
[src:abraham-kuyper/abraham-kuyper] He developed the so-called neo-Calvinism, which goes beyond conventional Calvinism on a number of issues.
[src:abraham-kuyper/abraham-kuyper] Furthermore, Kuyper made a significant contribution to the formulation of the principle of common grace in the context of a Calvinist world-view.
[src:abraham-kuyper/abraham-kuyper] Most important has been Kuyper's view on the role of God in everyday life.
[src:abraham-kuyper/abraham-kuyper] He believed that God continually influenced the life of believers, and daily events could show his workings.
[src:abraham-kuyper/abraham-kuyper] God's acts are necessary to ensure the continued existence of creation.
[src:abraham-kuyper/abraham-kuyper] Without his direct activity, creation would self-destruct.
[src:abraham-kuyper/abraham-kuyper] Kuyper's political ideals were orthodox-Protestant and anti-revolutionary.
[src:abraham-kuyper/abraham-kuyper] The concept of sphere sovereignty was very important for Kuyper.
[src:abraham-kuyper/abraham-kuyper] He rejected the popular sovereignty of France in which all rights originated with the individual, and the state-sovereignty of Germany in which all rights derived from the state.
[src:abraham-kuyper/abraham-kuyper] Instead, he wanted to honour the "intermediate bodies" in society, such as schools and universities, the press, business and industry, the arts etc., each of which would be sovereign in its own sphere.
[src:abraham-kuyper/abraham-kuyper] In the interest of a level playing field, he championed the right of every faith community (among whom he counted humanists and socialists) to operate their own schools, newspapers, hospitals, youth movements etc.
[src:abraham-kuyper/abraham-kuyper] He sought equal government finances for all faith-based institutions.
[src:abraham-kuyper/abraham-kuyper] He saw an important role for the state in upholding the morality of the Dutch people.
[src:abraham-kuyper/abraham-kuyper] He favoured monarchy, and saw the House of Orange as historically and religiously linked to the Dutch people.
[src:abraham-kuyper/abraham-kuyper] His commitment to universal suffrage was only tactical; he expected the Anti-Revolutionary Party would be able to gain more seats this way.
[src:abraham-kuyper/abraham-kuyper] In actuality, Kuyper wanted a Householder Franchise where fathers of each family would vote for his family.
[src:abraham-kuyper/abraham-kuyper] He also favoured a Senate representing the various interest, vocational and professional groups in society.
[src:abraham-kuyper/abraham-kuyper] With his ideals, he defended the interests of a group of middle class orthodox reformed, who were often referred to as "the little people" (*de kleine luyden*).
[src:abraham-kuyper/abraham-kuyper] He formulated the principle of antithesis: a divide between secular and religious politics.
[src:abraham-kuyper/abraham-kuyper] Liberals and socialists, who were opposed to mixing religion and politics, were his natural opponents.
[src:abraham-kuyper/abraham-kuyper] Catholics were a natural ally, for not only did they want to practice religiously inspired politics, but they also were no electoral opponent, because they appealed to different religious groups.
[src:abraham-kuyper/abraham-kuyper] Socialists, who preached class conflict, were a danger to the reformed workers.
[src:abraham-kuyper/abraham-kuyper] He called for workers to accept their fates and be happy with a simple life because the afterlife would be much more satisfying and revolution would only lead to instability.
[src:abraham-kuyper/abraham-kuyper] At the same time, he argued that the system of unrestricted free enterprise was in need of "architectonic critique" and he urged government to adopt labour legislation and to inspect workplaces.
[src:abraham-kuyper/abraham-kuyper] Kuyper's political views and acts have influenced Dutch politics.
[src:abraham-kuyper/abraham-kuyper] Kuyper stood at the cradle of pillarisation, the social expression of the anti-thesis in public life.
[src:abraham-kuyper/abraham-kuyper] His championing of parity treatment for faith-based organisations and institutions created the basis for the alliance between Protestants and Catholics that has dominated Dutch politics to the present day.
[src:abraham-kuyper/abraham-kuyper] One of the major political parties of the Netherlands, the CDA, is still heavily influenced by Kuyper's thought.
[src:abraham-kuyper/abraham-kuyper] There is still a small federation named the Continued Reformed Churches in the Netherlands which remains loyal to the foundations laid by Kuyper.
[src:abraham-kuyper/abraham-kuyper] In North America, Kuyper's political and theological views have had a significant impact, especially in the Reformed community.
[src:abraham-kuyper/abraham-kuyper] He is considered the father of Dutch Neo-Calvinism and had considerable influence on the thought of philosopher Herman Dooyeweerd.
[src:abraham-kuyper/abraham-kuyper] Others that have been influenced by Kuyper include Auguste Lecerf, Francis Schaeffer, Cornelius Van Til, Alvin Plantinga, Nicholas Wolterstorff, Albert M.
[src:abraham-kuyper/abraham-kuyper] Wolters, Vincent Bacote, Anthony Bradley, Chuck Colson, Timothy J.
[src:abraham-kuyper/abraham-kuyper] Tudur Jones, Bobi Jones, and the hip-hop artist Lecrae.
[src:abraham-kuyper/abraham-kuyper] In 2006, Reformed Bible College, located in Grand Rapids, Michigan was renamed in honor of Abraham Kuyper and is now Kuyper College.
[src:abraham-kuyper/abraham-kuyper] As well as Kuyper's profound influence upon European Christian-Democrat politics up to the present, his political theology was also crucial in the history of South Africa.
[src:abraham-kuyper/abraham-kuyper] His legacy in South Africa is arguably even greater than within the Netherlands.
[src:abraham-kuyper/abraham-kuyper] There, his Christian-National conception, centred upon the identification of the Afrikaner Calvinist community as the *kern der natie*, became a rallying position for the Dutch Reformed Church in South Africa.
[src:abraham-kuyper/abraham-kuyper] As Christian nationalists, Kuyper's adherents in South Africa were instrumental in the building of Afrikaner cultural, political and economic institutions to restore Afrikaner fortunes following the Boer War, which ultimately led to apartheid.
[src:abraham-kuyper/abraham-kuyper] Saul Dubow notes that Kuyper advocated "the commingling of blood" as "the physical basis for all higher development" in the Stone Lectures (1898).
[src:abraham-kuyper/abraham-kuyper] Harinck argues that "Kuyper was not guided by the cultural racism of his day, but by his Calvinistic creed of human equality".
[src:abraham-kuyper/abraham-kuyper] Kuyper's legacy includes a granddaughter, Johtje Vos, who is noted for having sheltered many Jews in her home in the Netherlands from the Nazis.
[src:abraham-kuyper/abraham-kuyper] After World War II she moved to New York City.
[src:abraham-kuyper/academic-administration] An administrative executive in charge of a university department or of some schools, may be termed a dean or some variation.
[src:abraham-kuyper/academic-administration] The chief executive of academic establishments other than universities, may be termed headmaster or head teacher (schools), director (used to reflect various positions ranging from the head of an institution to the head of a program), or principal, as used in primary education.
[src:abraham-kuyper/academic-administration] Like other professional areas, academic administration follows a specialized and often highly abstract terminology.
[src:abraham-kuyper/academic-administration] This terminology often depends on that used in military strategy (as in Strategic Planning) and business management (including Public Relations).
[src:abraham-kuyper/academic-administration] Digital era brings a communication overload and intense stresses of the job are threatening administrators mental or physical health.
[src:abraham-kuyper/academic-administration] Administrators are operating in an era of multiple continuing crises, unreliable supply chains etc.
[src:abraham-kuyper/academic-administration] Academic administrations are structured in various ways at different institutions and in different countries.
[src:abraham-kuyper/academic-administration] Full-time tertiary education administrators emerged as a distinct role in Australia from the mid-1970s, as institutions sought to deal with their increasing size and complexity, along with a broadening of their aspirations.
[src:abraham-kuyper/academic-administration] As the professionalism of tertiary administrators has developed, there has been a corresponding push to recognise the uniqueness and validity of their role in the academic environment.
[src:abraham-kuyper/academic-administration] As of 2004, general staff composed over half the employees at Australian universities.
[src:abraham-kuyper/academic-administration] There has recently been a shift in the preferred nomenclature for non-academic staff at Australian universities, from "general staff" to "professional staff".
[src:abraham-kuyper/academic-administration] It has been argued that the changing in role of the professional staff has been due to the changing work that they are performing, as professional staff assist students with technology.
[src:abraham-kuyper/academic-administration] The overarching body for all staff working in administration and management in Australia is the Association for Tertiary Education Management.
[src:abraham-kuyper/academic-administration] In Ireland, statutes for universities and technological universities set out roles for governing bodies, chief officers and academic councils.
[src:abraham-kuyper/academic-administration] For universities, the Universities Act 1997 provides that each university has a governing authority and that the functions of the university are performed by or on the directions of that authority.
[src:abraham-kuyper/academic-administration] The chief officer is appointed by the governing authority and may be called the president, provost or another title determined by the institution.
[src:abraham-kuyper/academic-administration] Each university also has an academic council which controls academic affairs, including curriculum, instruction and education, subject to statutory constraints and review by the governing authority.
[src:abraham-kuyper/academic-administration] A broadly similar model applies to technological universities.
[src:abraham-kuyper/academic-administration] Under the Technological Universities Act 2018, each technological university has a governing body and a chief officer called the president, and must have an academic council.
[src:abraham-kuyper/academic-administration] The academic council's statutory functions include control of academic affairs, programme development, recommendations on admissions and assessment regulations, and other academic functions delegated by the institution.
[src:abraham-kuyper/academic-administration] The Higher Education Authority Act 2022 also provides for system performance frameworks and performance agreements with designated institutions.
[src:abraham-kuyper/academic-administration] The structures for administration and management in higher education in the United Kingdom vary significantly between institutions.
[src:abraham-kuyper/academic-administration] Any description of a general structure will therefore not apply to some or even many institutions, and therefore any general statement of structures may be misleading.
[src:abraham-kuyper/academic-administration] Not all UK universities have the post of Registrar.
[src:abraham-kuyper/academic-administration] The Director of Finance may report to the Registrar or directly to the Vice-Chancellor, whilst other senior posts may or may not report to the Registrar.
[src:abraham-kuyper/academic-administration] This next tier of senior positions might include Directors of Human Resources, Estates, and Corporate Affairs.
[src:abraham-kuyper/academic-administration] The Academic Registrar is often included in this next tier.
[src:abraham-kuyper/academic-administration] Their role is mostly to accomplish student-facing administrative processes such as admissions, student records, complaints, and graduation.
[src:abraham-kuyper/academic-administration] The overarching body for all staff working in administration and management in the UK is the Association of University Administrators.
[src:abraham-kuyper/academic-administration] In the United States, a college or university is typically supervised by a president or chancellor who reports regularly to a board of trustees (made up of individuals from outside the institution) and who acts as chief executive officer.
[src:abraham-kuyper/academic-administration] Most large colleges and universities now use an administrative structure with a tier of vice presidents, among whom the provost (or vice president for academic affairs, or academic dean) as the chief academic officer.
[src:abraham-kuyper/academic-administration] Although the demographic picture of university leadership is changing, the majority of academic administrators remain middle-aged white men.
[src:abraham-kuyper/academic-administration] The ten highest-paid administrators at private colleges earn an average of about $2.5 million per year, while at public colleges the figure is $1.4 million.
[src:abraham-kuyper/academic-administration] These figures includes both base pay and other income.
[src:abraham-kuyper/academic-administration] Deans may supervise various and more specific aspects of the institution, or may be CEOs of entire campuses.
[src:abraham-kuyper/academic-administration] They may report directly to the president or chancellor.
[src:abraham-kuyper/academic-administration] In some cases a provost supervises the institution's entire academic staff, occupying a position generally superior to any dean.
[src:abraham-kuyper/academic-administration] In other instances the Dean of a College may be the equivalent to a Provost or Vice Chancellor or Vice President for Academic Affairs.
[src:abraham-kuyper/academic-administration] Below deans in the administrative hierarchy are heads of individual academic departments and of individual administrative departments.
[src:abraham-kuyper/academic-administration] These heads (commonly styled "chairs" or "directors") then supervise the faculty and staff of their individual departments.
[src:abraham-kuyper/academic-administration] The Chair of a department is typically a tenured or at least tenure-track faculty member, supported by administrative staff.
[src:abraham-kuyper/academic-administration] The number of administrators on university campuses has grown dramatically in recent decades, one reason that the rise in college tuition costs has outstripped the rate of inflation.
[src:abraham-kuyper/adam-stegerwald] Stegerwald was born the son of a farmer in Greußenheim in Lower Franconia and attended primary school there between 1881 and 1888 before completing an apprenticeship as a carpenter in Würzburg.
[src:abraham-kuyper/adam-stegerwald] From 1900 to 1902, Stegerwald studied economics under Lujo Brentano at the Ludwig-Maximilians-Universität München.
[src:abraham-kuyper/adam-stegerwald] He began his engagement with the labour movement in 1893, when he joined the Catholic *Gesellenverein*, a non-union Catholic labour society, in Günzburg.
[src:abraham-kuyper/adam-stegerwald] From 1896, he was part of the workers' electoral association of the Centre Party in Munich, where he was committed to building the burgeoning Catholic trade union movement.
[src:abraham-kuyper/adam-stegerwald] He advanced quickly, becoming honorary chairman of the Central Union of Christian Woodworkers in 1899 and, in 1903, general-secretary of the General Association of German Christian Trade Unions, a position he retained until 1929.
[src:abraham-kuyper/adam-stegerwald] In his political role, he steered a conservative course, supporting the Empire and its colonial ambitions.
[src:abraham-kuyper/adam-stegerwald] He attempted to unify the non-socialist unions, such as the Protestant DHV and the Catholic *Gesellvereine*, into a unified organisation to create a counterweight to the socialist free trade unions, though he was unsuccessful.
[src:abraham-kuyper/adam-stegerwald] He supported the German war effort in the First World War and served on the board of the Wartime Food Office from 1916 to 1919, as well as in the Prussian House of Lords during the final year of the war.
[src:abraham-kuyper/adam-stegerwald] In the aftermath of the November Revolution, Stegerwald represented the Catholic trade unions in co-signing the 15 November working agreement between the unions and employers' associations.
[src:abraham-kuyper/adam-stegerwald] The working agreement set out a common understanding between labour and capital, acknowledging unions as the legitimate representatives of the workers and setting out the basis for collective bargaining agreements and the eight-hour day.
[src:abraham-kuyper/adam-stegerwald] Throughout the following year Stegerwald called for the end to the workers' council movement which was popular among many radical workers, mostly in the socialist unions.
[src:abraham-kuyper/adam-stegerwald] In 1919, he became head of the German Trade Union Federation (DGB), the reorganised Christian trade union federation.
[src:abraham-kuyper/adam-stegerwald] Initially, it bore a close resemblance to Stegerwald's prewar proposal of a broad non-socialist union federation, including the Catholic unions as well as the liberal Hirsch-Duncker unions and the Protestant white-collar associations.
[src:abraham-kuyper/adam-stegerwald] However, the more secular Hirsch-Duncker unions departed in November, leaving the DGB largely dominated by the Catholic unions with a deeply conservative Protestant minority in the German National Association of Commercial Employees (DHV).
[src:abraham-kuyper/adam-stegerwald] As leader of the DGB, Stegerwald struggled to maintain the unity of the federation's conflicting parts.
[src:abraham-kuyper/adam-stegerwald] Left-wing elements such as the Catholic miners' and industrial unions resented Stegerwald's conservative orientation and his continuous attempts to find common cause with conservative Protestants rather than seek better conditions for workers.
[src:abraham-kuyper/adam-stegerwald] At the same time, he sought constantly to appease the ultraconservative white-collar DHV.
[src:abraham-kuyper/adam-stegerwald] In 1927, he sided with the DGB's industrial unions in opposing a widely-agreed wage increase for civil servants.
[src:abraham-kuyper/adam-stegerwald] This effort failed and alienated him from the white-collar elements of the DGB, to whom he had previously been a stalwart ally.
[src:abraham-kuyper/adam-stegerwald] After becoming chair of the Centre's Reichstag delegation in January 1929, he resigned from his union positions.
[src:abraham-kuyper/adam-stegerwald] He was succeeded as chair of the DGB by Heinrich Imbusch, leader of the miners' union.
[src:abraham-kuyper/adam-stegerwald] Stegerwald was elected to both the national and Prussian constituent assembles early in 1919, and became minister for public welfare in Prussia under Social Democratic minister-president Paul Hirsch.
[src:abraham-kuyper/adam-stegerwald] At the DGB congress in 1920, Stegerwald proposed the formation of an inter-denominational "People's Party", through which he hoped to unite both Catholics and Protestants in a conservative project opposed to socialism, liberalism, and materialism.
[src:abraham-kuyper/adam-stegerwald] The idea was roundly rejected: the right wing of the Centre opposed abandoning their Catholic orientation while the left-wing feared the conservative, anti-labour orientation of such a party.
[src:abraham-kuyper/adam-stegerwald] Nonetheless, Stegerwald remained a convinced advocate of a pan-Christian party for the rest of his life.
[src:abraham-kuyper/adam-stegerwald] During the government impasse following the 1921 Prussian state election, the state Centre Party drafted Stegerwald to serve as interim Minister-President.
[src:abraham-kuyper/adam-stegerwald] He was tasked with putting together a cabinet including Social Democrats, the Centre, the left-liberal Democrats, and the conservative German People's Party.
[src:abraham-kuyper/adam-stegerwald] He was invested by the Landtag with a large majority in April, but soon came to blows with the Social Democrats, who withdrew their support.
[src:abraham-kuyper/adam-stegerwald] His cabinet consisted of a minority government of the Centre and Democrats, and negotiations to expand it stalled out toward the end of the year.
[src:abraham-kuyper/adam-stegerwald] It finally collapsed in October when the Democrats quit in protest against Stegerwald's proposal to hand the interior ministry to the Social Democrats.
[src:abraham-kuyper/adam-stegerwald] He resigned, and in short order a new centre-left government was formed under Social Democrat Otto Braun.
[src:abraham-kuyper/adam-stegerwald] This proved to be the end of Stegerwald's involvement in Prussian state politics.
[src:abraham-kuyper/adam-stegerwald] Stegerwald strongly advocated for the Centre to form part of a conservative government in the Reich under Hans Luther, using his role as head of the DGB to claim widespread union support.
[src:abraham-kuyper/adam-stegerwald] For this he received a cold reception at the October 1924 congress of the DGB's industrial unions and was attacked by Heinrich Imbusch, head of the miners' union.
[src:abraham-kuyper/adam-stegerwald] Ultimately the unions passed a resolution declaring neutrality in political affairs and Stegerwald was forced to walk back his previous statements.
[src:abraham-kuyper/adam-stegerwald] When the first Luther cabinet was invested the following January, the majority of the labour representatives among the Centre's Reichstag delegation did not support it.
[src:abraham-kuyper/adam-stegerwald] At the Centre Party congress in November 1925 Stegerwald was heckled by Joseph Wirth, outspoken leader of the Centre left, who accused him of giving a pass to nationalist extremism.
[src:abraham-kuyper/adam-stegerwald] After the collapse of the Luther cabinet the following year, Stegerwald's perspective on cooperation with the conservative right changed.
[src:abraham-kuyper/adam-stegerwald] He no longer considered the German National People's Party "worthy of carrying Christian spirit in public life", finding the party both anti-Catholic and uninterested in serious advocacy for the Protestant churches or Christian values.
[src:abraham-kuyper/adam-stegerwald] In December 1928, the Centre Party congress was tasked with electing a new party chairman.
[src:abraham-kuyper/adam-stegerwald] The executive unanimously recommended Stegerwald.
[src:abraham-kuyper/adam-stegerwald] This choice was intended to be a fig leaf to the unions and facilitate Stegerwald's movement out of the DGB leadership into full-time politics, which he had long sought.
[src:abraham-kuyper/adam-stegerwald] However, the party national committee rejected Stegerwald: this was at least in part due to the predominance of civil servants on the committee, whose interests Stegerwald had unexpectedly opposed the previous year.
[src:abraham-kuyper/adam-stegerwald] He was also opposed for reasons of personality as well as his opposition to church interference in the party.
[src:abraham-kuyper/adam-stegerwald] The party hierarchy considered several alternatives and ultimately put forward three names to a floor vote: Stegerwald, his rival in the unions Joseph Joos, and prelate Ludwig Kaas.
[src:abraham-kuyper/adam-stegerwald] Stegerwald received 42 votes, Joos 92, and Kaas 182.
[src:abraham-kuyper/adam-stegerwald] Despite this defeat, in January 1929, Stegerwald was elected head of the Centre Reichstag faction.
[src:abraham-kuyper/adam-stegerwald] He resigned his position as head of the DGB and in the unions, finally completing his move to full-time politics.
[src:abraham-kuyper/adam-stegerwald] In April he became Minister for Transport in the new Great Coalition under Hermann Müller.
[src:abraham-kuyper/adam-stegerwald] When the government fell in March 1930, Stegerwald was promoted to Labour Minister by new Chancellor Heinrich Brüning, who had been Stegerwald's assistant and protege earlier in the 1920s.
[src:abraham-kuyper/adam-stegerwald] In this role he was both tasked with implementing the government's harsh austerity response to the Great Depression in Germany, which entailed reductions in wages and rolling back labour rights, while also seeking to maintain the welfare state for the millions of unemployed despite harsh cutbacks.
[src:abraham-kuyper/adam-stegerwald] It was also in this time that he achieved the long-sought for cooperation with the moderate and religious elements of the Protestant right following the secession from the DNVP of the Conservative People's Party and CSVD, who collaborated in the Brüning government.
[src:abraham-kuyper/adam-stegerwald] Stegerwald remained Labour Minister until the cabinet's dismissal in May 1932.
[src:abraham-kuyper/adam-stegerwald] Following Hitler's appointment as Chancellor in January 1933, Stegerwald was attacked by SA storm troopers at an election rally in Krefeld on 21 February.
[src:abraham-kuyper/adam-stegerwald] The following month, he helped lead negotiations with the Nazi Party to secure the Centre's support for the Enabling Act of 1933 which handed *de facto* dictatorial power to Hitler.
[src:abraham-kuyper/adam-stegerwald] From 1933 to 1934 he was indicted, along with Wilhelm Marx and Heinrich Brauns, in the trial of the Cologne *Volksverein Verlag* in his capacity as board member of the National Association for Catholic Germany.
[src:abraham-kuyper/adam-stegerwald] He was on the list of politicians to be purged during the Night of the Long Knives, but received warning and disappeared into exile for three months.
[src:abraham-kuyper/adam-stegerwald] He retired to Franconia during the regime, and in letters to former colleagues urged church leaders to appease the government for fear of the churches' dissolution.
[src:abraham-kuyper/adam-stegerwald] Following the 20 July plot, he was temporarily arrested under the *Aktion Gitter*.
[src:abraham-kuyper/adam-stegerwald] From August to October 1944 he was detained by the Gestapo in Würzburg prison before being released.
[src:abraham-kuyper/adam-stegerwald] Following the end of the Second World War, the American occupation authority appointed the 71-year-old Stegerwald administrator of the Lower Franconia district.
[src:abraham-kuyper/adam-stegerwald] He became leader of the "Würzburg group" which proved instrumental in the foundation of the Christian Social Union in Bavaria in the late summer and autumn of 1945.
[src:abraham-kuyper/adam-stegerwald] In Stegerwald's speeches and writing it was clear he considered the new party the fulfillment of his "People's Party" concept of 1920, serving as a "bridge" between denominations, classes, and generations; he coined the name "Christian Social Union".
[src:abraham-kuyper/adam-stegerwald] Despite the desire of some Catholic labour leaders to found a united labour party with the socialist unions, and of other Catholic leaders to re-found the Centre Party, Stegerwald's model was ultimately taken up nationwide in the form of the Christian Democratic Union of Germany.
[src:abraham-kuyper/adam-stegerwald] Adam Stegerwald died of pneumonia in December 1945.
[src:abraham-kuyper/adam-stegerwald] He has been honoured extensively, with streets named after him in numerous towns and cities across Germany.
[src:abraham-kuyper/adam-stegerwald] Two political education foundations, the Adam Stegerwald Circle and Stegerwald Foundation, are named in his honour.
[src:abraham-kuyper/adam-stegerwald] A neighbourhood in Cologne, *Stegerwaldsiedlung*, is also named for him.
[src:abraham-kuyper/adam-stegerwald] Two buildings in Würzburg are named *Adam-Stegerwald-Haus*: the office of the regional CSU branch as well as a student accommodation building.
[src:abraham-kuyper/adam-stegerwald] Another building in Königswinter, originally acquired by Jakob Kaiser and used by Catholic welfare and political associations in the Weimar period, was renamed *Adam-Stegerwald-Haus* in 1948 after its acquisition by the new German Trade Union Confederation.
[src:abraham-kuyper/adam-stegerwald] After housing a number of different organisations over the decades, the building was sold in 2015 and converted into a nursing home, retaining its name.
